03710nam a22006255i 9780271056807DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710568077 a10.1515/97802710568072doi  a(DE-B1597)583702  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJK2063b.S44 2011eb 7aPOL0080002bisacsh04a342.73/0552221 aSeery, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aToo Young to Run? :bA Proposal for an Age Amendment to the U.S. Constitution /cJohn Seery. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2015] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 History -- t2 Theory -- t3 Politics -- tPostscript: An Appeal to U.S. Civics Educators -- tAppendix 1: Federal Age Requirements in Other Democracies -- tAppendix 2: Average Age of Congress Since 1949 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUnder the Constitution of the United States, those with political ambitions who aspire to serve in the federal government must be at least twenty-five to qualify for membership in the House of Representatives, thirty to run for the Senate, and thirty-five to become president. What is the justification for these age thresholds, and is it time to consider changing them? In this provocative and lively book, John Seery presents the case for a constitutional amendment to lower the age barrier to eighteen, the same age at which citizens become eligible to vote. He divides his argument into three sections. In a historical chapter, he traces the way in which the age qualifications became incorporated in the Constitution in the first place. In a theoretical chapter, he analyzes the normative arguments for office eligibility as a democratic right and liberty. And in a political chapter, he ruminates about the real-world consequences of passing such an amendment and the prospects for its passage. Finally, in a postscript, he argues that younger citizens in particular ought to be exposed to this fundamental issue in civics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aNominations for officezUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271056807423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271056807.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK